        heading: 'Defining and Measuring Retail Shrinkage',
        body: 'Retail shrinkage — the difference between recorded (book) inventory and actual physical inventory — represents a significant financial drain on small retailers, typically ranging from 1% to 3% of revenue. The four primary causes of shrinkage are external theft (shoplifting), internal theft (employee pilferage), administrative errors (incorrect receiving, pricing, or inventory recording), and vendor fraud (short deliveries or billing discrepancies). Accurate estimation of total shrinkage and its attribution across these causes is prerequisite to effective loss prevention, yet most small retailers rely solely on periodic physical inventory counts to assess shrinkage — a practice that provides only aggregate, after-the-fact measurement with no diagnostic granularity. PoS data, when properly integrated with inventory records, receiving logs, and vendor invoices, enables continuous shrinkage monitoring at the SKU level. The fundamental equation is straightforward: for any SKU over any period, expected ending inventory equals beginning inventory plus received quantities minus sold quantities (from PoS) minus known removals (transfers, waste, markdowns). The discrepancy between this expected inventory and the physical count is the measured shrinkage, and its pattern across SKUs, time periods, and operational dimensions provides diagnostic information about likely causes. askbiz.co automates this perpetual inventory reconciliation, computing expected inventory continuously from PoS and receiving records and flagging discrepancies for investigation.',
